{"title_page": "HMS Fortune (1913)", "text_new": "{{short description|Acasta-class destroyer}}\n{{other ships|HMS Fortune}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=[[File:HMS Fortune (1913).jpg|300px|HMS Fortune]]\n|Ship caption=HMS ''Fortune'' in pre-war black paint, and without pennant number\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United Kingdom\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|United Kingdom|naval}}\n|Ship name=HMS ''Fortune''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder=[[Fairfield Shipbuilding and Engineering Company]], [[Govan]]\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=488<ref name=CBD>{{cite web|url=http://www.clydesite.co.uk/clydebuilt/viewship.asp?id=290|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526064131/http://www.clydesite.co.uk/clydebuilt/viewship.asp?id=290|url-status=usurped|archive-date=26 May 2011|title=HMS ''Fortune'' at Clyde-built database|accessdate=14 November 2015}}</ref>\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=17 March 1913\n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship recommissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship refit=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=Sunk by {{SMS|Westfalen}} at Battle of Jutland on 1 June 1916\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Acasta|destroyer}}\n|Ship displacement={{convert|1072|t|LT|abbr=on}}\n|Ship length={{convert|267|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|27|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draught={{convert|9|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship power=*4 \u00d7 Yarrow-type water-tube boilers\n*{{convert|24500|ihp|kW|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=\n* Parsons steam turbines\n* 2 shafts\n|Ship speed={{convert|29|kn|abbr=on}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship complement=73\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=\n* 3 \u00d7 [[QF 4 inch naval gun Mk IV, XII, XXII|QF {{convert|4|in|mm|adj=on|sigfig=4}} L/40 Mark IV guns]], mounting P Mk. IX\n* 1 \u00d7 [[QF 2 pounder naval gun|QF 2 pdr pom-pom]] Mk. II\n* 2 \u00d7 single tubes for [[British 21 inch torpedo|21 inch (533 mm)]] [[torpedo]]es\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''HMS ''Fortune''''' was an {{sclass-|Acasta|destroyer}}, and the twenty-first ship of the Royal Navy to bear the name. She was launched in 1913 and was sunk at the [[Battle of Jutland]] in 1916.\n\n==Design and description==\nThe ''Acasta''s were larger and heavier armed than the preceding H and I classes ({{sclass-|Acorn|destroyer|5}} and {{sclass-|Acheron|destroyer|5}}, respectively), displacing about 25% more and with the mixed calibre armament replaced with a uniform fit of [[British ordnance terms#QF|QF]] 4-inch guns, which the ''Acasta''s introduced. Previous {{convert|4|in|mm|adj=on|0}} weapons had been of the breech-loading ([[British ordnance terms#BL|BL]]) type. The guns were shipped one each on the [[forecastle]] and either side abreast the after torpedo tube (or amidships before and after the tube in some ships.) All ships had three funnels, the foremost being tall and narrow, the second short and wide and the third level with the second but narrower. The foremost torpedo tube was sited between the second and third funnels, a distinctive feature of this class.\n\nThere were twelve 'standard' vessels built to a common Admiralty design, and eight builders' specials that (except for ''Garland'') had a shorter, less beamy hull; five of the latter were from [[John I. Thornycroft & Company Limited|Thornycroft]] with {{convert|22500|shp|abbr=on}} (one of Thornycroft's ships, {{HMS|Hardy|1912|2}}, was planned to [[diesel engine|diesel]] cruising motors, but these were not ready in time and ''Hardy'' was completed with Thornycroft's standard machinery).<ref name=\"Friedman p126-9\">Friedman 2009, pp. 126\u2013129.</ref> One by [[Parsons Marine Steam Turbines|Parsons]] ({{HMS|Garland|1913|2}}) had semi-geared turbines<ref name=\"Friedman p127\">Friedman 2009, p. 127.</ref> giving a speed of {{convert|31|kn|lk=in}} on trials, with a seventh from [[Fairfield Shipbuilding and Engineering Company|Fairfields]] had a clipper bow. The eighth 'special' was {{HMS|Ardent|1913|2}} by [[William Denny and Brothers|William Denny]], Dumbarton, which was built using [[longitudinal framing]] rather than conventional transverse framing. While ''Ardent''{{'s}} novel construction seems to have been a success, no more destroyers were built for the Royal Navy using longitudinal framing until the [[J, K and N-class destroyer|J-class destroyers]] in the 1930s.<ref name=\"Friedman p127\"/><ref name=\"brown p70-1\">Brown 2010, pp. 70\u201371.</ref>\n\n''Fortune'' [[Displacement (ship)|displaced]] {{convert|1072|t|LT}} with a [[Length overall|length]] of {{convert|267|ft|6|in|m}}, a [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|27|ft|m}} and a [[Draft (ship)|draught]] of {{convert|9|ft|6|in|m}}. The destroyer had a complement of 73.<ref name=conway>Gardiner and Gray, p. 75</ref>\n\nThe ship was powered by four [[Yarrow boiler|Yarrow-type water-tube boilers]] which fed [[Parsons Marine Steam Turbine Company|Parsons]] [[steam turbine]]s rated at {{convert|24500|shp|kW|lk=in}}, which drove two shafts,<ref name=conway/> giving the destroyer a maximum speed of {{convert|29|kn}}. ''Fortune'' was given an experimental clipper [[Bow (ship)|bow]]<ref name=conway/>\n\n''Fortune'' was armed with three [[QF 4 inch naval gun Mk IV, XII, XXII|QF {{convert|4|in|mm|adj=on|sigfig=4}} L/40 Mark IV guns]] on P Mk. IX mountings. However, ''Fortune'' was a \"Builders' Special\", and the second 4-inch gun was mounted on a platform between the no.2 and 3 funnels. The ship one [[QF 2 pounder naval gun|QF 2 pdr pom-pom]] Mk. II gun. The destroyer was also equipped with two single [[torpedo tube]]s for four [[British 21 inch torpedo|21 inch (533 mm)]] [[torpedo]]es.<ref name=conway/>\n\n==Construction and career==\n''Fortune'' was [[Keel laying|laid down]] under the 1911&ndash;1912 construction programme by [[Fairfield Shipbuilding and Engineering Company]] and [[Ship naming and launching|launched]] on 17 March 1913.<ref name=AS/> She was temporarily renamed HMS ''Kismet'' in October 1913, but this was reverted shortly afterwards.<ref name=AS/>\n\nShe joined the [[4th Destroyer Flotilla]] on completion and served with the [[Grand Fleet]] on the outbreak of [[World War I]].\n\n===Battle of Jutland and loss===\nDuring the evening of 31 May 1916, the 4th Flotilla was screening the rear of the Grand Fleet in the [[Battle of Jutland]], against the [[Imperial German Navy]]'s [[High Seas Fleet]]. At 11:20 pm, the 4th Flotilla encountered unknown ships off their starboard quarter. Believing them to be British, the [[flotilla leader]] {{HMS|Tipperary|1915|2}} flashed a challenge. Six opposing ships, comprising the [[battleship]]s {{SMS|Westfalen||2}}, {{SMS|Nassau||2}} and {{SMS|Rheinland||2}} and three cruisers, turned on their floodlights and opened up with their secondary armament. Most aimed for ''Tipperary'' which was soon ablaze. The destroyers began to return fire and launched a torpedo attack, which led to a collision among the Germans.<ref>Massie, pp. 642\u20133</ref>\n\nDuring this first attack, ''Fortune'' and {{HMS|Ardent|1913|2}} were separated from the rest of the flotilla. They began to look for the German ships which had disengaged after battering their way through the 4th Flotilla.<ref name=Massie1>Massie, p. 644</ref> About 11:30 pm<ref name=BC>{{cite web|url=http://www.battleships-cruisers.co.uk/destroyers_before_1900.htm|title=Battleships-Cruisers.co.uk website - Destroyers before 1918|accessdate=15 November 2015}}</ref> they eventually found four large ships and engaged them. Both ''Ardent'' and ''Fortune'' were sunk in the ensuing firefight. The last anyone saw of ''Fortune'' was the ship afire but still firing as the destroyer was sinking.<ref name=Massie1/>\n\nThe wrecksite is designated as a ''protected place''<ref>{{cite web |title= Statutory Instrument 2008/0950 | work=Office of Public Sector Information, 1 April 2008  | url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/si/si2008/uksi_20080950_en_1 | accessdate=15 November 2015}}</ref> under the [[Protection of Military Remains Act 1986]].\n\n==Pennant numbers==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n!Pennant Number<ref name=AS>{{cite web|url=http://www.gwpda.org/naval/s0450000.htm|title=''\"Arrowsmith\" List'': Royal Navy WWI Destroyer Pendant Numbers|accessdate=2009-02-27}}</ref>||From|||To\n|-\n|H30||6 December 1914&nbsp;&nbsp;||31 May 1916\n|}\n\n==References==\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* Brown, David K. (2010) ''The Grand Fleet: Warship Design and Development 1906\u20131922''. Barnsley, UK: Seaforth Publishing. {{ISBN|978-1-84832-085-7}}.\n* Friedman, Norman. (2009) ''British Destroyers: From Earliest Days to the Second World War'', Barnsley, UK: Seaforth Publishing. {{ISBN|978-1-84832-049-9}}.\n* Gardiner, Robert & Gray, Randal, eds. (1985). ''Conway's All the World's Fighting Ships: 1906\u20131921.'' Annapolis, Maryland: Naval Institute Press. {{ISBN|0-85177-245-5}}.\n* Massie, Robert K. (2003). ''Castles of Steel: Britain, Germany, and the Winning of the Great War at Sea.'' New York: Ballantine Books. {{ISBN|0-345-40878-0}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.jutlandcrewlists.org/fortune Battle of Jutland Crew Lists Project - HMS Fortune Crew List]\n{{Acasta class destroyer}}\n{{June 1916 shipwrecks}}\n{{coord missing|North Sea}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fortune 1913}}\n[[Category:Acasta-class destroyers]]\n[[Category:World War I destroyers of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1916]]\n[[Category:Ships sunk at the Battle of Jutland]]\n[[Category:Protected Wrecks of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1913 ships]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Acasta-class destroyer}}\n{{other ships|HMS Fortune}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=[[File:HMS Fortune (1913).jpg|300px|HMS Fortune]]\n|Ship caption=HMS ''Fortune'' in pre-war black paint, and without pennant number\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United Kingdom\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|United Kingdom|naval}}\n|Ship name=HMS ''Fortune''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder=[[Fairfield Shipbuilding and Engineering Company]], [[Govan]]\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=488<ref name=CBD>{{cite web|url=http://www.clydesite.co.uk/clydebuilt/viewship.asp?id=290|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526064131/http://www.clydesite.co.uk/clydebuilt/viewship.asp?id=290|url-status=usurped|archive-date=26 May 2011|title=HMS ''Fortune'' at Clyde-built database|accessdate=14 November 2015}}</ref>\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=17 March 1913\n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship recommissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship refit=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=Sunk by {{SMS|Westfalen}} at Battle of Jutland on 1 June 1916\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Acasta|destroyer}}\n|Ship displacement={{convert|1072|t|LT|abbr=on}}\n|Ship length={{convert|267|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|27|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draught={{convert|9|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship power=*4 \u00d7 Yarrow-type water-tube boilers\n*{{convert|24500|ihp|kW|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=\n* Parsons steam turbines\n* 2 shafts\n|Ship speed={{convert|29|kn|abbr=on}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship complement=73\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=\n* 3 \u00d7 [[QF 4 inch naval gun Mk IV, XII, XXII|QF {{convert|4|in|mm|adj=on|sigfig=4}} L/40 Mark IV guns]], mounting P Mk. IX\n* 1 \u00d7 [[QF 2 pounder naval gun|QF 2 pdr pom-pom]] Mk. II\n* 2 \u00d7 single tubes for [[British 21 inch torpedo|21 inch (533 mm)]] [[torpedo]]es\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''HMS ''Fortune''''' was an {{sclass-|Acasta|destroyer}}, and the twenty-first ship of the Royal Navy to bear the name. She was launched in 1913 and was sunk at the [[Battle of Jutland]] in 1916.\n\n==Design and description==\nThe ''Acasta''s were larger and heavier armed than the preceding H and I classes ({{sclass-|Acorn|destroyer|5}} and {{sclass-|Acheron|destroyer|5}}, respectively), displacing about 25% more and with the mixed calibre armament replaced with a uniform fit of [[British ordnance terms#QF|QF]] 4-inch guns, which the ''Acasta''s introduced. Previous {{convert|4|in|mm|adj=on|0}} weapons had been of the breech-loading ([[British ordnance terms#BL|BL]]) type. The guns were shipped one each on the [[forecastle]] and either side abreast the after torpedo tube (or amidships before and after the tube in some ships.) All ships had three funnels, the foremost being tall and narrow, the second short and wide and the third level with the second but narrower. The foremost torpedo tube was sited between the second and third funnels, a distinctive feature of this class.\n\nThere were twelve 'standard' vessels built to a common Admiralty design, and eight builders' specials that (except for ''Garland'') had a shorter, less beamy hull; five of the latter were from [[John I. Thornycroft & Company Limited|Thornycroft]] with {{convert|22500|shp|abbr=on}} (one of Thornycroft's ships, {{HMS|Hardy|1912|2}}, was planned to [[diesel engine|diesel]] cruising motors, but these were not ready in time and ''Hardy'' was completed with Thornycroft's standard machinery).<ref name=\"Friedman p126-9\">Friedman 2009, pp. 126\u2013129.</ref> One by [[Parsons Marine Steam Turbines|Parsons]] ({{HMS|Garland|1913|2}}) had semi-geared turbines<ref name=\"Friedman p127\">Friedman 2009, p. 127.</ref> giving a speed of {{convert|31|kn|lk=in}} on trials, with a seventh from [[Fairfield Shipbuilding and Engineering Company|Fairfields]] had a clipper bow. The eighth 'special' was {{HMS|Ardent|1913|2}} by [[William Denny and Brothers|William Denny]], Dumbarton, which was built using [[longitudinal framing]] rather than conventional transverse framing. While ''Ardent''{{'s}} novel construction seems to have been a success, no more destroyers were built for the Royal Navy using longitudinal framing until the [[J, K and N-class destroyer|J-class destroyers]] in the 1930s.<ref name=\"Friedman p127\"/><ref name=\"brown p70-1\">Brown 2010, pp. 70\u201371.</ref>\n\n''Fortune'' [[Displacement (ship)|displaced]] {{convert|1072|t|LT}} with a [[Length overall|length]] of {{convert|267|ft|6|in|m}}, a [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|27|ft|m}} and a [[Draft (ship)|draught]] of {{convert|9|ft|6|in|m}}. The destroyer had a complement of 73.<ref name=conway>Gardiner and Gray, p. 75</ref>\n\nThe ship was powered by four [[Yarrow boiler|Yarrow-type water-tube boilers]] which fed [[Parsons Marine Steam Turbine Company|Parsons]] [[steam turbine]]s rated at {{convert|24500|shp|kW|lk=in}}, which drove two shafts,<ref name=conway/> giving the destroyer a maximum speed of {{convert|29|kn}}. ''Fortune'' was given an experimental clipper [[Bow (ship)|bow]]<ref name=conway/>\n\n''Fortune'' was armed with three [[QF 4 inch naval gun Mk IV, XII, XXII|QF {{convert|4|in|mm|adj=on|sigfig=4}} L/40 Mark IV guns]] on P Mk. IX mountings. However, ''Fortune'' was a \"Builders' Special\", and the second 4-inch gun was mounted on a platform between the no.2 and 3 funnels. The ship one [[QF 2 pounder naval gun|QF 2 pdr pom-pom]] Mk. II gun. The destroyer was also equipped with two single [[torpedo tube]]s for four [[British 21 inch torpedo|21 inch (533 mm)]] [[torpedo]]es.<ref name=conway/>\n\n==Construction and career==\n''Fortune'' was [[Keel laying|laid down]] under the 1911&ndash;1912 construction programme by [[Fairfield Shipbuilding and Engineering Company]] and [[Ship naming and launching|launched]] on 17 March 1913.<ref name=AS/> She was temporarily renamed HMS ''Kismet'' in October 1913, but this was reverted shortly afterwards.<ref name=AS/>\n\nShe joined the [[4th Destroyer Flotilla]] on completion and served with the [[Grand Fleet]] on the outbreak of [[World War I]].\n\n===Battle of Jutland and loss===\nDuring the evening of 31 May 1916, the 4th Flotilla was screening the rear of the Grand Fleet in the [[Battle of Jutland]], against the [[Imperial German Navy]]'s [[High Seas Fleet]]. At 11:20pm, the 4th Flotilla encountered unknown ships off their starboard quarter. Believing them to be British, the [[flotilla leader]] {{HMS|Tipperary|1915|2}} flashed a challenge. Six opposing ships, comprising the [[battleship]]s {{SMS|Westfalen||2}}, {{SMS|Nassau||2}} and {{SMS|Rheinland||2}} and three cruisers, turned on their floodlights and opened up with their secondary armament. Most aimed for ''Tipperary'' which was soon ablaze. The destroyers began to return fire and launched a torpedo attack, which led to a collision among the Germans.<ref>Massie, p.642-3</ref>\n\nDuring this first attack, ''Fortune'' and {{HMS|Ardent|1913|2}} were separated from the rest of the flotilla. They began to look for the German ships which had disengaged after battering their way though the 4th Flotilla.<ref name=Massie1>Massie, p.644</ref> About 11:30pm<ref name=BC>{{cite web|url=http://www.battleships-cruisers.co.uk/destroyers_before_1900.htm|title=Battleships-Cruisers.co.uk website - Destroyers before 1918|accessdate=15 November 2015}}</ref> they eventually found four large ships and engaged them. Both ''Ardent'' and ''Fortune'' were sunk in the ensuing firefight. The last anyone saw of ''Fortune'' was the ship afire but still firing as the destroyer was sinking.<ref name=Massie1/>\n\nThe wrecksite is designated as a ''protected place''<ref>{{cite web |title= Statutory Instrument 2008/0950 | work=Office of Public Sector Information, 1 April 2008  | url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/si/si2008/uksi_20080950_en_1 | accessdate=15 November 2015}}</ref> under the [[Protection of Military Remains Act 1986]].\n\n==Pennant numbers==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n!Pennant Number<ref name=AS>{{cite web|url=http://www.gwpda.org/naval/s0450000.htm|title=''\"Arrowsmith\" List'': Royal Navy WWI Destroyer Pendant Numbers|accessdate=2009-02-27}}</ref>||From|||To\n|-\n|H30||6 December 1914&nbsp;&nbsp;||31 May 1916\n|}\n\n==References==\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* Brown, David K. (2010) ''The Grand Fleet: Warship Design and Development 1906\u20131922''. Barnsley, UK: Seaforth Publishing. {{ISBN|978-1-84832-085-7}}.\n* Friedman, Norman. (2009) ''British Destroyers: From Earliest Days to the Second World War'', Barnsley, UK: Seaforth Publishing. {{ISBN|978-1-84832-049-9}}.\n* Gardiner, Robert & Gray, Randal, eds. (1985). ''Conway's All the World's Fighting Ships: 1906\u20131921.'' Annapolis, Maryland: Naval Institute Press. {{ISBN|0-85177-245-5}}.\n* Massie, Robert K. (2003). ''Castles of Steel: Britain, Germany, and the Winning of the Great War at Sea.'' New York: Ballantine Books. {{ISBN|0-345-40878-0}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.jutlandcrewlists.org/fortune Battle of Jutland Crew Lists Project - HMS Fortune Crew List]\n{{Acasta class destroyer}}\n{{June 1916 shipwrecks}}\n{{coord missing|North Sea}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fortune 1913}}\n[[Category:Acasta-class destroyers]]\n[[Category:World War I destroyers of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1916]]\n[[Category:Ships sunk at the Battle of Jutland]]\n[[Category:Protected Wrecks of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1913 ships]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo: though\u2192through; ,mos", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HMS_Fortune_(1913)"}
{"title_page": "List of NSWRL/ARL/SL/NRL premiership captains and coaches", "text_new": "This is a '''list of captains and coaches of [[National Rugby League]] premiership winning teams''', as well as its predecessors [[New South Wales Rugby League premiership|NSWRL]], [[Australian Rugby League|ARL]] and [[Super League (Australia)|Super League]]. [[Ken Kearney]] has captained the most premierships with six, all at [[St. George Dragons|St. George]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/ken-kearney/summary.html|title=Ken Kearney - Career Stats & Summary - Rugby League Project|website=www.rugbyleagueproject.org|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> while [[Arthur Halloway]] has coached the most premierships with eight, four at [[Sydney Roosters|Eastern Suburbs]] and four at [[Balmain Tigers|Balmain]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/coaches/arthur-halloway/summary.html|title=Arthur James Halloway - 'Pony' - Summary - Rugby League Project|website=www.rugbyleagueproject.org|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nIn the early years, quite a few teams had [[Player-coach|captain-coaches]] who would play and coach at the same time. In this list, they are counted as both the captain and the coach.\n\n== List ==\n'''Source:'''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Middleton|first=David|title=2019 Official Rugby League Annual|publisher=|year=2019|isbn=|location=|pages=206\u2013207}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Premiers\n!Captain\n!Coach\n|-\n|2019\n|{{Leagueicon|Sydney|16}} [[Sydney Roosters]]\n|[[Boyd Cordner]]/[[Jake Friend]]\n|[[Trent Robinson]]\n|-\n|2018\n|{{Leagueicon|Sydney|16}} [[Sydney Roosters]]\n|[[Boyd Cordner]]/[[Jake Friend]]\n|[[Trent Robinson]]\n|-\n|2017\n|{{Leagueicon|Melbourne|16}} [[Melbourne Storm|Melbourne]]\n|[[Cameron Smith]]\n|[[Craig Bellamy (rugby league)|Craig Bellamy]]\n|-\n|2016\n|{{Leagueicon|Cronulla|16}} [[Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks|Cronulla]]\n|[[Paul Gallen]]\n|[[Shane Flanagan]]\n|-\n|2015\n|{{Leagueicon|No